Zawgyi Keyboard Installation Guide
----------------------------------

For Users:
---------

To install zawgyi-keyboard

The Downloaded zawgyi-kb*.deb would be in ~/Desktop or somewhere else.

Change to your Path

$ cd /path-to-your-zawgyi-kb*.deb/
$ sudo dpkg -i zawgyi-kb*.deb

or 

double-click on the debian package zawgyi-kb*.deb


Post installation

Go to System -> Preferences-> Keyboard, click on Keyboard, then Keyboard Preferences would be appear.
Go to Layout Tab and click on Add button. Choose a Layout “Myanmar” and press Add button.
You will have both US English Layout and Myanmar Zawgyi Layout. To get keyboard switching and Third Level chooser,
press Layout Options in the Layout Tab of Keyboard Preferences. Check e.g. Shift+Alt Change Layout in Layout Switching
and Check e.g. Any-Wins key in Third Level Chooser. It depend on you and your preferences. Then you can work with both of English and Zawgyi Keyboard.

If you want to get Keyboard Indicator on your panel, right-click on Panel and click on “Add to Panel”. Search Keyboard Indicator and press it to add.
You will see Keyboard Indicator on your Panel.


Testing Zawgyi Keyboard

You can test some words in Gedit to know if it corrects or not. When you get correct words, it is done.

If you don't know Zawgyi Keyboard Layout,
Go to Applications > System Tools > Zawgyi Keyboard
You will see the lastest zawgyi keyboard map by opening zawgyikeyboard.pdf.

Having a lot of fun with your zawgyi-keyboard!! :-)


For Package Makers:
------------------

download zawgyi-kb_0.1.1.tar.gz from http://code.google.com/p/zawgyi-keyboard/

$ cd /path-to-zawgyi-kb_0.1.1.tar.gz/

$ tar xvzf zawgyi-kb_0.1.1.tar.gz

$ cd zawgyi-kb-0.1.1

$ dh_make -e <your.maintainer@email> -f ../zawgyi-kb_0.1.1.tar.gz

$ rm debian/*.ex debian/*.EX

$ rm debian/dirs debian/README.Debian

See editing 'control' and 'changelog' with below references

$ fakeroot debian/rules clean

$ fakeroot debian/rules binary

or

$ debuild -k<keyid>


If you are new to Debian Package, you may want to read the following artiles.
http://www.linuxdevices.com/articles/AT8047723203.html
http://www.debian-administration.org/articles/336
http://www.debian-administration.org/article/Rolling_your_own_Debian_packages_part_2
http://www.debian-administration.org/articles/251
http://www.debian.org/doc/maint-guide/index.en.html#contents
https://help.ubuntu.com/community/GnuPrivacyGuardHowto




